\n**WHAT'S GOING ON**\nAmazon just threw out the old, static spreadsheets and charts that sellers used to run their stores [1]. They replaced them with something called an \"agentic AI canvas\" inside Seller Central [1]. \"Agentic\" is just a fancy computer science word meaning the software doesn't just answer questions like a normal chatbot; it can actually reason, plan, and press the buttons for you [4]. If a seller asks, \"Should I restock?\", the AI instantly builds a custom visual dashboard showing exactly what happens to cash flow, stockouts, and storage fees if demand drops by ten percent [2]. Then, once the seller picks a path, the AI goes ahead and executes the actual restock orders or price changes on their behalf [2]. \n\n**WHY THIS IS A BIG DEAL**\nOver 60 percent of everything bought on Amazon comes from independent sellers, mostly small and medium-sized businesses [3]. For a long time, running these shops meant drowning in a sea of data\u2014guessing how much inventory to buy or what ads to run. Now, the AI acts like a high-end financial analyst that works for free [3]. It uses Amazon's own massive computing brain, called Bedrock, to run \"what if\" simulations in real time [2, 5]. It takes the pure guesswork out of launching new products and optimizing ad campaigns, which means mom-and-pop shops can suddenly operate with the ruthless, data-driven efficiency of a massive corporation [6, 7]. \n\n**UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH**\nIf the machine is smart enough to predict your sales, simulate your pricing, and execute your inventory orders, what exactly is the human seller doing? The uncomfortable reality is that sellers are handing the steering wheel directly over to the very platform that controls their marketplace [2, 4]. Amazon claims sellers already accept the AI's recommendations nearly 90 percent of the time [4]. When you blindly trust the house algorithm to set your prices and buy your marketing ads, you have to wonder if the AI is optimizing strictly for *your* profit margin, or for Amazon's overall machine [4, 6]. We don't really know exactly how the underlying algorithms balance those conflicting interests.\n\n**SO WHAT**\nThe day-to-day job of an Amazon seller just shifted from manually pushing buttons to managing a digital brain that runs the store for them [2, 4].",
